{
  "id": 16,
  "name": "Prepare for transfer",
  "notes": [
    "DMS (Dimethyl Sulfide) is created in wort whenever it is heated. It is an off-flavor that has the aroma of cooked corn. When the wort is still boiling, DMS is boiled off so it will not end up in the beer.",
    "After the boil DMS is still created while the beer is warm, but it is no longer evaporated. Therefore, we want to cool the beer as quickly as possible.",
    "But first we'll sanitize the transfer path to the fermenter. Connect your transfer hose to the output. If the hose is long enough to reach the BK, hang it in the kettle. Otherwise, catch the hot wort in a clean bucket and put it back in the BK afterwards.",
    "By first transfering some boiling hot wort without cooling (and back into the BK), you'll sanitize your transfer hose and CFC."
  ],
